```

## Web Visualization

Start the local visualization page from the repository root:

```powershell
python -m src.web_visualizer --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8765
```

Then open:

```text
http://127.0.0.1:8765
```

The web page is a display and orchestration layer only. It does not change the
model or training logic. Existing runs are read from `outputs/`, including
`run_summary.json`, `cluster_penalty_probs.csv`, and optional
`prediction_intermediates.npz`.

The page can also launch training through the existing entry point. By default
it runs:

```powershell
F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat run --no-capture-output -n my_fram python -m src.train --config <generated-config>
```

The generated config is written under `outputs/web_visualizer/runs/<run_id>/`,
keeps CUDA as the default device (`cuda:0`), enables prediction intermediates,
and sets `eval.skip_test=false` so the inference replay data can be produced.
Replay samples use `diagnostics.prediction_sample_strategy=stratified_random`:
the test windows are split into `prediction_sample_count` ranges and one sample
is selected from each range, avoiding a block of nearly identical consecutive
windows.
The web launcher also sets `MOELOSS_PROGRESS_FORCE=1` and `PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1`
for that subprocess only, so the training log streams epoch, batch, loss, and
the current epoch progress bar into `train.log` and the browser progress panel.
After training finishes, refresh the page or result list to inspect MoE
participation and prediction replay.

If the Conda path or environment name differs, override them before starting the
web service:

```powershell
$env:MOE_VIS_CONDA_BAT = "F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat"
$env:MOE_VIS_CONDA_ENV = "my_fram"
python -m src.web_visualizer --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8765
```

## PKR-MoE Configuration

A typical residual MoE section:

```yaml
moe:
  enable: true
  topk: 1
  select_ranks: [1]
  gate_route_on_penalty_only: true
  pred_side_residual:
    enable: true
    feature_mode: legacy
    alpha_scale: 1.1
    selection_policy: val_mse_gate
    detach_routed_penalty_pred: false
penalties:
  enabled:
    - level
    - trend
    - direction
```

Important fields:

- `penalties.enabled` defines the penalty candidate pool.
- `moe.topk` and `select_ranks` control which penalty routes can be selected.
- `pred_side_residual.selection_policy` controls validation-based residual
  selection.
- `detach_routed_penalty_pred=false` keeps the prediction-side residual path
  coupled to training.

Current parameter accounting note: the implementation instantiates residual
adapter parameters for each `(cluster, penalty)` pair. The train-only top-k prior
restricts routing and activation, not physical parameter allocation.

## Transfer Experiments

Transfer uses source-trained PKR-MoE checkpoints and target train-only
normalization/clustering.

Example entry points:

```powershell
F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat run -n my_fram python -m src.transfer --config configs\ETTm1ToETTh1.yaml
F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat run -n my_fram python -m src.transfer --config configs\ETTm1ToETTh2.yaml
F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat run -n my_fram python -m src.transfer --config configs\ETTm1ToETTm2.yaml
F:\Anaconda3\condabin\conda.bat run -n my_fram python -m src.transfer --config configs\ETTm2ToETTm1.yaml
```

The paper summary reports zero-shot and fine-tune metrics separately. Fine-tune
learning-rate selection is performed only across fine-tune runs; zero-shot is
reported directly, not selected against fine-tune.

## Paper Tables and Reports

Main generated artifacts:

```text
outputs/experiment_excel_summary/paper_style_experiment_summary.md
outputs/experiment_excel_summary/table8c_parameter_comparison.csv
outputs/experiment_excel_summary/transfer_table9_finetune_val_selected.csv
outputs/ett_interpretability_report/ett_interpretability_report.md
outputs/ett_interpretability_report/penalty_participation_summary.csv
outputs/ett_interpretability_report/run_improvement_summary.csv
```

Useful generators:

```powershell
python scripts\transfer_finetune_table.py --allow-missing-lrs
python scripts\summarize_ett_interpretability.py --best-results outputs\ett_interpretability_report\best_results_ett_h96_h192.csv --out-root outputs\ett_interpretability_report
```

Table highlights currently tracked in the paper summary:

- Table 1: main ETT forecasting results.
- Table 2: Weather and Electricity results.
- Table 2b: comparison with iTransformer, TimeMixer, PatchTST, and other
  baselines.
- Tables 3-6: component ablations.
- Table 7: clustering ablation.
- Table 8: multi-seed stability.
- Table 8b: lightweight significance check.
- Table 8c: full-model parameter comparison.
- Table 9: ETTm1/ETTm2 source transfer.
- Table 10: H=96/192 interpretability summary.
- Table 11: penalty utilization, skip probability, and dominant penalty lambda.

## Testing

Run focused tests for table and report generation:

```powershell
python -m pytest tests\test_transfer_finetune_table.py -q
python -m pytest tests\test_parameter_overhead_table.py -q
python -m pytest tests\test_ett_interpretability_summary.py -q
```

The local `my_fram` environment may not include `pytest`; in that case use the
base Python environment for tests and keep model-running commands in `my_fram`.

## Development Notes

- Keep generated experiment outputs separate from code changes.
- Do not mix no-leak main results with calibration or KNN/hybrid diagnostics.
- When updating paper tables, regenerate the corresponding CSV/Markdown source
  and check that table scopes match their descriptions.
- When changing adapter allocation logic, rerun parameter accounting because the
  current count assumes `(cluster, penalty)` adapter instantiation.
